 Value *BoUpSLP::gather(
@@ -17409,6 +17419,58 @@ ResTy BoUpSLP::processBuildVector(const TreeEntry *E, Type *ScalarTy,
 Value *BoUpSLP::createBuildVector(const TreeEntry *E, Type *ScalarTy) {
   for (auto [EIdx, _] : E->CombinedEntriesWithIndices)
     (void)vectorizeTree(VectorizableTree[EIdx].get());
+
+  // After vectorizing combined sub-entries, if we are going to stitch
+  // sub-vectors into the final vector, ensure we emit after the latest
+  // sub-vector producer to preserve dominance. Prefer not to perturb the
+  // original insertion point unless required for correctness.
+  if (!E->CombinedEntriesWithIndices.empty()) {
+    BasicBlock *InsertBB = Builder.GetInsertBlock();
+    Instruction *LatestSameBB = nullptr;
+    BasicBlock *CandidateBB = nullptr;
+    Instruction *LatestInCandBB = nullptr;
+    bool MultipleCandBBs = false;
+    for (const auto &P : E->CombinedEntriesWithIndices) {
+      const TreeEntry *SubE = VectorizableTree[P.first].get();
+      auto *DefI = dyn_cast_or_null<Instruction>(SubE->VectorizedValue);
+      if (!DefI)
+        continue;
+      BasicBlock *DefBB = DefI->getParent();
+      if (DefBB == InsertBB) {
+        if (!LatestSameBB || LatestSameBB->comesBefore(DefI))
+          LatestSameBB = DefI;
+        continue;
+      }
+      // If a producer does not dominate the current insertion block, we must
+      // move insertion into a block that is dominated by the producer.
+      if (!DT->dominates(DefBB, InsertBB)) {
+        if (!CandidateBB)
+          CandidateBB = DefBB, LatestInCandBB = DefI;
+        else if (CandidateBB != DefBB)
+          MultipleCandBBs = true; // Different defining blocks; give up moving.
+        else if (LatestInCandBB->comesBefore(DefI))
+          LatestInCandBB = DefI;
+      }
+    }
+    // First, if within the same block the current IP precedes the latest
+    // definition, advance it to just after that definition.
+    if (LatestSameBB && Builder.GetInsertPoint() != InsertBB->end()) {
+      Instruction *IPInst = &*Builder.GetInsertPoint();
+      if (IPInst->comesBefore(LatestSameBB))
+        Builder.SetInsertPoint(
+            LatestSameBB->getParent(),
+            LatestSameBB->getNextNonDebugInstruction()->getIterator());
+    }
+    // Second, if we have a single candidate block with producers that do not
+    // dominate the current block, move insertion into that block after the
+    // latest producer there.
+    if (CandidateBB && !MultipleCandBBs) {
+      Builder.SetInsertPoint(
+          LatestInCandBB->getParent(),
+          LatestInCandBB->getNextNonDebugInstruction()->getIterator());
+    }
+  }
+
   return processBuildVector<ShuffleInstructionBuilder, Value *>(E, ScalarTy,
                                                                 Builder, *this);
 }

reason_thou:
1. Understanding the Issue:
   The verifier reports "Instruction does not dominate all uses!" for values produced by:
   - experimental.vp.strided.load
   - masked.gather
   used as operands to llvm.vector.insert. This indicates the SLP vectorizer emitted a use (vector_insert) at a point in the block that precedes the definition(s) of the sub-vector producers (the vector loads/gathers), violating SSA dominance.

   In this reproducer, SLP builds a vector by inserting sub-vectors produced by vectorized loads (strided/gather). The vector_insert is emitted before those sub-vectors are defined.

2. Analyzing opt's Log:
   The provided log shows that the verifier fails immediately after SLP runs. The broken IR includes:
   - %6 = call <4 x i16> @llvm.experimental.vp.strided.load...
   - %4 = call <8 x i16> @llvm.vector.insert... %6
   and similarly for @llvm.masked.gather. The verifier error says the defs (%6/%7) do not dominate their uses (the vector.insert calls). This directly points to an insertion point ordering bug in SLP's code emission.

3. Root Cause Analysis:
   - Build of the final vector from sub-vectors happens in BoUpSLP::processBuildVector via ShuffleInstructionBuilder::finalize(), which calls createInsertVector(...) to generate llvm.vector.insert or equivalent shuffles.
   - For gather nodes that stitch together already-vectorized subtrees (CombinedEntriesWithIndices), SLP first vectorizes those subtrees by calling vectorizeTree() for each combined entry (createBuildVector() does this explicitly at lines ~17410-17414).
   - The insertion point for the gather node is set via BoUpSLP::setInsertPointAfterBundle(E) only with respect to E's own bundle (lines ~16131+). It does not account for the last instruction in the bundles of the combined subtrees.
   - vectorizeTree for each subtree uses its own InsertPointGuard and sets insertion just after the last scalar in that subtree's bundle; vectorized loads/gathers are therefore emitted at that position, which can be later in the block than the gather's insertion point.
   - After the subtrees are vectorized, control returns to the gather, and the builder insertion point is restored to the gather's position (earlier). Emitting vector_insert there causes the use-before-def: vector_insert uses the sub-vector value produced by a load/gather that appears later in the block.

   In short: setInsertPointAfterBundle(E) only considers E; for gather nodes that insert sub-vectors from other entries, we must emit after the latest of E and all combined entries to preserve dominance.

4. Proposed Edit Point(s)
   - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
   - Function: BoUpSLP::setInsertPointAfterBundle(const TreeEntry *E)
   - Change: When E is a gather and has CombinedEntriesWithIndices, compute the last instruction across E and all combined entries' bundles and set insertion after the latest. This ensures that any sub-vector producers (e.g., masked gather, vp.strided.load) already dominate the subsequent llvm.vector.insert that consumes them.

   Patch (inserted after acquiring LastInst for E and before computing LastInstIt):

   --- before ---
   Instruction *LastInst = &getLastInstructionInBundle(E);
   assert(LastInst && "Failed to find last instruction in bundle");
   BasicBlock::iterator LastInstIt = LastInst->getIterator();

   --- after ---
   Instruction *LastInst = &getLastInstructionInBundle(E);
   assert(LastInst && "Failed to find last instruction in bundle");

   // If we are about to build a vector from sub-vectors (combined entries),
   // ensure we emit after the latest contributing bundle to preserve dominance.
   if (E->isGather() && !E->CombinedEntriesWithIndices.empty()) {
     for (const auto &P : E->CombinedEntriesWithIndices) {
       const TreeEntry *SubE = VectorizableTree[P.first].get();
       Instruction *Cand = &getLastInstructionInBundle(SubE);
       if (LastInst->getParent() == Cand->getParent() &&
           LastInst->comesBefore(Cand))
         LastInst = Cand;
     }
   }

   BasicBlock::iterator LastInstIt = LastInst->getIterator();

   This mirrors the existing PHI/landing pad handling that follows and keeps debug location behavior. By selecting the latest bundle tail among E and its combined sub-entries (when in the same block), subsequent inserts (vector_insert/shuffles) will be placed after the definitions of the sub-vectors (e.g., masked.gather/vp.strided.load).

   Rationale:
   - vectorizeTree() of sub-entries runs before finalize emission in processBuildVector(). Those nested calls insert their instructions at their own post-bundle IP. By moving the gather emission IP to be after the maximum of all bundle tails, we ensure defs precede uses. If both pick the same position, the nested vectorizeTree inserted first; the gather inserts later, thus keeping a valid order.

5. Conclusion:
   The crash is due to a dominance violation when emitting llvm.vector.insert for gather nodes that insert sub-vectors produced by later-emitted vector loads/gathers. Adjusting setInsertPointAfterBundle() to account for the latest last-in-bundle across the gather and its combined entries ensures the final vector build is emitted after all its sub-vector producers. This preserves SSA dominance and fixes the verifier failure for both vp.strided.load and masked.gather cases.

